relations.target: development=00251126-n (act of improving by expanding or enlarging or refining; \""he congratulated them on their development of a plan to meet the emergency\""; \""they funded research and development\"");00950022-n (the act of making some area of land or water more profitable or productive or useful; \""the development of Alaskan resources\""; \""the exploitation of copper deposits\"");07082671-n ((music) the section of a composition or movement (especially in sonata form) where the major musical themes are developed and elaborated);07438160-n (a recent event that has some relevance for the present situation; \""recent developments in Iraq\""; \""what a revolting development!\"");08566645-n (a district that has been developed to serve some purpose; \""such land is practical for small park developments\"");13485760-n (processing a photosensitive material in order to make an image visible; \""the development and printing of his pictures took only two hours\"");13486023-n (a process in which something passes by degrees to a different stage (especially a more advanced or mature stage); \""the development of his ideas took many years\""; \""the evolution of Greek civilization\""; \""the slow development of her skill as a writer\"");13510240-n ((biology) the process of an individual organism growing organically; a purely biological unfolding of events involved in an organism changing gradually from a simple to a more complex level; \""he proposed an indicator of osseous development in children\"");14446275-n (a state in which things are improving; the result of developing (as in the early part of a game of chess); \""after he saw the latest development he changed his mind and became a supporter\""; \""in chess your should take care of your development before moving your queen\""

stage=01651668-v (plan, organize, and carry out (an event); \""the neighboring tribe staged an invasion\"");01715304-v (perform (a play), especially on a stage; \""we are going to stage `Othello'\"");00307726-n (a section or portion of a journey or course; \""then we embarked on the second stage of our Caribbean cruise\"");04303700-n (a large platform on which people can stand and can be seen by an audience; \""he clambered up onto the stage and got the actors to help him into the box\"");04304087-n (a small platform on a microscope where the specimen is mounted for examination);04304236-n (a large coach-and-four formerly used to carry passengers and mail on regular routes between towns; \""we went out of town together by stage about ten or twelve miles\"");07019828-n (the theater as a profession (usually `the stage'); \""an early movie simply showed a long kiss by two actors of the contemporary stage\"");08664141-n (any scene regarded as a setting for exhibiting or doing something; \""All the world's a stage\""--Shakespeare; \""it set the stage for peaceful negotiations\"");13962925-n (a specific identifiable position in a continuum or series or especially in a process; \""a remarkable degree of frankness\""; \""at what stage are the social sciences?\"");15315573-n (any distinct time period in a sequence of events; \""we are in a transitional stage in which many former ideas must be revised or rejected\""

reversion=00069153-n (a failure to maintain a higher state);00236075-n (returning to a former state);00347519-n (turning in the opposite direction);07358174-n (a reappearance of an earlier characteristic);07441173-n ((genetics) a return to a normal phenotype (usually resulting from a second mutation));13362365-n ((law) an interest in an estate that reverts to the grantor (or his heirs) at the end of some period (e.g., the death of the grantee)
